Macedonians vote in a referendum if they change the name of the country.
The Macedonian people voted on Sunday in a referendum on whether they wanted to change their name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbors represents a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The governments of the two countries reached an agreement in June on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents claim that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has raised doubts about whether the result will reach the minimum 50 percent needed for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum ballot was: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to gain admission to entities such as the EU or NATO of Macedonia, one of the emerging countries from the fall of Yugoslavia.
"Today I came to vote for the future of the country, for the youth of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because that means a safer life for all of us", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, several members of parliament said they would accept the result of the vote and make it final.
A change of nine would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said that as of 1 p.m. there were no irregularities.
However, turnout was only 16 percent, compared to 34 percent in the last parliamentary election in 2016, when 66 percent of registered voters cast their ballots.
"I came to vote for my children, our place is in Europe", declared Gjose Tanevski, a 62-year-old voter from the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote for the Macedonian referendum on the country's name change that would pave the way for its accession to the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia, on 30 September 2018.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small stage and placed chairs in front of the tents set up for those who boycotted the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads held high and not through the service door", Kavadarkov added.
We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries like China and Russia and join the Eurasian Union.
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I think the overwhelming majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of joining the EU and NATO", Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive result would be "confirmation of our future".
A poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Political Research revealed that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the referendum, which is below the required figure.
Another poll by the Macedonian Telma television network indicated that 57 percent of those polled planned to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For the referendum to be valid, the result must be 50 percent plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would represent the first major blow to the pro-Western government's policy since it came to power in May of last year.
