John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens.
Private schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another crop of outstanding test scores, only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible standard of education for pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the careers they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
But if you speak to him in his own language, it will reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people in other countries.
From the results of the recent exams this year, we can see that languages are at the top of the board and with the highest pass rates in private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages got an A.
Data, collected from the 74 schools that make up the SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained an honors degree in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and see them as key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages are being given the same consideration as subjects like science, technology, engineering and math in the curricula of private schools and all sorts of other subjects.
A survey by the UK Employment and Training Commission in 2014 indicated that amongst the reasons employers find it difficult to fill vacancies, lack of language skills accounts for 17%.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that require languages.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you learn a second language you will have a real advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will put a bilingual person directly ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for kids today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, gives children more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, the languages of instruction differ according to school.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others opt for languages considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what your children's interests are, private schools always have several languages to choose from and teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish private schools specialise in providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future may hold.
We cannot deny that at this moment, in a global business environment, languages remain vitally important for the future of a country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
You gotta do it right.
