"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the US", he added.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disarmament first on our part".
While Ri was echoing well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization whereby North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had occurred with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an acting US president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean Peninsula while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its coercive aim, even though it opposes 'declaration of end of war'", Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for those who don't know us.
But the problem is that the continuing sanctions are sharpening our distrust.
Ri did not mention plans for the second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier in the week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the other side of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have reached a dead end.
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after "evil President" Trump called Kim "rocket man on a suicide mission".
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much work to be done and that sanctions should be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
Trump said on Wednesday that there was no deadline for that, and that it takes two years, three months, five months".
China and Russia are discussing whether the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, on Thursday US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council that: "The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue firmly and without exception until we see complete, final and verified denuclearisation".
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
