Harvard students are conducting a course on getting enough rest.
This year, a new course at Harvard University is making all of its students sleep more in order to combat the growing macho culture of caffeinated all-night study.
One scholar found that students at the world's number one university often do not know the basics about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of the year, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?'
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which launched for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
One section is a picture of a dorm room, where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, trainers and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of the night-time pride still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students that sleep deprivation entailed was a growing problem.
Ensuring that they get enough and good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, she points out, even preventing them from gaining weight, since lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, causing them to be constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push a course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to bed and when to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
