China has reported a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
It affects more than 820,000 people in the country, health authorities said.
40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, marking a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to virtually zero, Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
Yet, year-on-year, the number of people living with HIV or AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was discriminated against in China in 1997, but they say discrimination against LGBT people has spread.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies estimate that 70 to 90 percent of men who have sex with men will eventually marry women.
Many of the transmission of the disease comes from inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV mediation as part of an effort to address the problem.
