What is the Global Citizen Festival and did it do something to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event that features an impressive cast of performers and an equally impressive mission to end global poverty.
In its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will see thousands of people flock to Central Park's Great Lawn, not only to enjoy performances by the likes of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness about the event's real goal of ending poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you want to pay for a VIP ticket), the audience attending had to complete a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or any other meaningful way to help raise awareness about their goal of ending poverty.
But what is the success rate of Global Citizen 12 years after achieving its goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a genuine way to persuade people to demand action, or is it just another case of what's called "clictivism", people who think they're making a difference by signing an online petition or tweeting?
Since 2011, Global Citizen says it has logged more than 19 million "shares" from its followers, driving a set of different goals.
It says these actions have helped to stimulate world leaders to announce commitments and policies equivalent to over $37 billion set to influence the lives of over 2.25 billion people by 2030.
As of early 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements stemming from its actions, of which at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that so far the guaranteed funds have had a direct impact on almost 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based investor and executive society that has pledged to "help children develop to their full potential", pledging to provide Rwanda with $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizen.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national authorities and Global Citizen supporters like you, we can turn the social injustice of malnutrition into a footnote in history", The Power of Nutrition ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in April 2018 in London.
The group also said that after more than 5000 actions were taken to improve maternal and child nutrition in the UK, the government announced funding for The Power of Nutrition project which will reach 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the most frequently asked questions on their website, "What makes you think we can end extreme poverty?"
Global Citizen responded: "It's going to be a long and hard road and at times we'll fall and fail.
But just like the great anti-apartheid and civil rights movements before us, we will succeed, because together, we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B and Janelle Monáe are some of the artists performing at this year's event in New York, which will be hosted by Deborra-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
