The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "online personal data store" or POD.
Contacts lists, to-do lists, calendars, music, and other personal and professional tools may be included.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
All of this makes this personal data warehouse unique in that the user has complete control over who can access what information.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to its chairman John Bruce, is that the company should bring appropriate resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security company owned by IBM, a few contracted developers to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
