The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
A new study being conducted on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to forage.
It is hoped that the results will shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to track the bats' activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be drawn to create a landscape-scale detailed picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor at NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating grasslands and what is the best way to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
The animals are threatened by construction and development that affect their nests and habitat loss.
Air generators and lighting are also a risk, as are glue fly traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts who conduct periodic surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organisation even has Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Threave we have a big bat area", he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive".
It stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the property, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single maternity nest can kill up to 400 females and young, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There is still much to learn about bats, and in the case of many of the species, we don't know how their populations are doing".
