The chorus goes on, "Move, move, I'm feeding the babies, move, move, I'm moving my friends".
However, the announcement, which was posted on the company's Facebook page, sparked controversy on social media.
With 77,000 views and hundreds of comments, the video has generated mixed reactions from viewers, many of whom said it highlights the "horrors" of the dairy sector.
"Using cows to advertise this product was a very mediocre decision.
Like us, they need to get pregnant and give birth to produce milk, but in their case we steal their babies days after they give birth", wrote one.
The Elvie milk extractor can be placed discreetly inside a breast pump (Elvie/mother)
Another viewer commented: "Clearly traumatic for mother and baby.
But yes, why not use them to advertise a milk extractor for mothers who stay with their babies?"
Another viewer added: "What a tactless announcement".
Other viewers defended the advert, even one woman claiming that she found the song "very funny".
"I think that's a great idea.
If I was still breastfeeding, I'd buy one.
Pulling out my milk made me feel exactly like a cow.
The ad is a little silly, but I interpreted it as a joke.
I think it's a great product", one wrote.
Another commented: "This is a funny ad for mothers who pump their milk (often in their workplaces or bathrooms) and feel like 'cows.'
This is not an advertisement to praise or judge the dairy industry".
At the end of the video, this group of women reveals that they were dancing with discreet extractors inserted into their braces.
The concept behind the campaign is that many women who suckle their milk say they feel like cows.
However, the Elvie extractor is completely silent, has no wires or tubes, and can be discreetly fitted into a breast brace, giving women the freedom to move around, hold their babies, and even walk around while they are sucking.
Ana Balarin, partner and executive creative director of Mother commented: "The Elvie extractor is such a revolutionary product that it deserves a bold and provocative launch.
In describing the parallels between women and dairy cows, we wanted to focus on milk extraction and all the challenges that it entails while also demonstrating in a fun way and close to the incredible sense of freedom that the new extractor will offer.
