Federal prosecutors are seeking to apply a rarely applied death penalty to the suspect in a terrorist attack in New York City.
Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Sayfullo Saipov, the suspect in the New York City terrorist attack that killed eight people, a sentence not carried out in the state since 1953.
Saipov, 30, allegedly used a Home Depot rental truck to carry out an attack on a bike lane on Lower Manhattan's West Side Highway, killing pedestrians and cyclists he encountered in his path in October.
To justify the death penalty, prosecutors will have to prove that Saipov "intentionally" killed the eight victims and caused them serious injury "intentionally", according to the notice of intent for the death penalty request filed in the Southern District of New York.
Both crimes involve the possibility of the death penalty being applied according to the court document.
Weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury indicted Saipov on 22 counts, including eight counts of murder in collaboration with an organized crime group, a practice commonly used by prosecutors in organized crime cases, and one count of assault and destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack required "remarkable planning and premeditation", prosecutors said in describing the manner in which Saipov carried out the "heinous, cruel and depraved" attack.
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov caused injury, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco", according to the notice of intent to prosecute.
Five of the victims were Argentine tourists.
The Southern District of New York hasn't had a death penalty case in a decade.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of murdering two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was applied in a federal case in New York was in 1953, in the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a couple who were executed after being convicted of conspiracy to commit espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, who was born in Uzbekistan, showed no remorse in the days and months following the attack, according to court documents.
He told investigators he felt good about what he had done, police said.
Saipov told authorities that he was inspired to carry out the attack by ISIS videos he viewed on his phone, according to the indictment.
He also requested to be allowed to see the ISIS flag in his hospital room, police said.
He pleaded not guilty to 22 counts.
David Patton, one of the federal public defender representing Saipov, indicated that they were "obviously disappointed" with the prosecution's decision.
"We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty rather than accept a guilty plea with life imprisonment without the possibility of parole will only prolong the trauma caused by these events for all those involved", Patton commented.
Saipov's defense team had previously asked prosecutors not to seek the death penalty.
